# replace empty with NA
df[df==""] <- NA
head(df,5)
tail(df,5)
df_confirmed <- df[df$current_status=="Laboratory-confirmed case",]

Let’s first explore the people having COVID19 symptoms changing over month

df_positive_test <- df_confirmed[-which(is.na(df_confirmed$pos_spec_dt)),]
df_symptom <- df_confirmed[-which(is.na(df_confirmed$onset_dt)),]

df_positive_test$positive_month <- month(as.POSIXlt(as.character(df_positive_test$pos_spec_dt), format="%Y/%m/%d"))
df_symptom$symptom_month <- month(as.POSIXlt(as.character(df_symptom$onset_dt), format="%Y/%m/%d"))

positive_test = rep(0,10)
symptom = rep(0,10)
for (m in 1:10){
  positive_test[m] = sum(df_positive_test$positive_month==m)
  symptom[m] = sum(df_symptom$symptom_month==m)
}

barplot(symptom,names.arg=1:10, ylab = "positive cases show symptoms", xlab="month in 2020")

# death rate ~ symptom month
df_symptom = df_symptom[union(which(df_symptom$death_yn=="No"),which(df_symptom$death_yn=="Yes")),]
death_rate = rep(0,10)
for (m in 1:10){
  df_temp = df_symptom[df_symptom$symptom_month==m,]
  death_rate[m] = sum(df_temp$death_yn=="Yes")/dim(df_temp)[1]
}
barplot(death_rate,names.arg=1:10, ylab = "death rate for patients with sympotoms", xlab="month in 2020")

df_survival_age_medcond = na.omit(data.frame(df_confirmed$death_yn, df_confirmed$age_group, df_confirmed$medcond_yn))
df_survival_age_medcond[df_survival_age_medcond=="Missing"|df_survival_age_medcond=="Unknown"]<- NA
df_survival_age_medcond = na.omit(df_survival_age_medcond)
head(df_survival_age_medcond)
age_range = as.character(unique(df_survival_age_medcond$df_confirmed.age_group))

We can see Feb, March, April, May, these 4 months have much higher death rate.

Does hospital really help reducing death rate?

# death_yn, age_group, hosp_yn, remove NA, missing and unknown values.

df_hosp = na.omit(data.frame(df_confirmed$death_yn, df_confirmed$age_group, df_confirmed$hosp_yn))
df_hosp[df_hosp=="Missing"|df_hosp=="Unknown"]<- NA
df_hosp = na.omit(df_hosp)

# hospitalize vs death rate

# Hospitalize ~ Age

hosp = df_hosp[df_hosp$df_confirmed.hosp_yn=="Yes",]
non_hosp = df_hosp[df_hosp$df_confirmed.hosp_yn=="No",]

# hospitalize vs death rate
sum(hosp$df_confirmed.death_yn =="Yes")/dim(hosp)[1]
## [1] 0.3193417
sum(non_hosp$df_confirmed.death_yn =="Yes")/dim(non_hosp)[1]
## [1] 0.01146518
# hospitalized ~ age
hosp_age = rep(0,length(age_range))
# head(hosp)
for (y in 1:length(age_range)){
  hosp_age[y] = dim(hosp[as.character(hosp$df_confirmed.age_group)==age_range[y],])[1]
}
barplot(hosp_age,names.arg=age_range, ylab = "Number of people hospitalized", xlab="age range")

for th people hospitalized and not hospitalized, death rate change with respect to age?

# people hospitalized, death rate in age?
hosp_death_rate = rep(0,length(age_range))
for (y in 1:length(age_range)){
  df_temp = hosp[as.character(hosp$df_confirmed.age_group)==age_range[y],]
  hosp_death_rate[y] = sum(df_temp$df_confirmed.death_yn=="Yes")/dim(df_temp)[1]
}
barplot(hosp_death_rate,names.arg=age_range, ylab = "Hospitalized death rate", xlab="age range", ylim=c(0,1))

# people not hospitalized, death rate in age?
non_hosp_death_rate = rep(0,length(age_range))
for (y in 1:length(age_range)){
  df_temp = non_hosp[as.character(non_hosp$df_confirmed.age_group)==age_range[y],]
  non_hosp_death_rate[y] = sum(df_temp$df_confirmed.death_yn=="Yes")/dim(df_temp)[1]
}
barplot(non_hosp_death_rate,names.arg=age_range, ylab = "Non hospitalized death rate", xlab="age range", ylim=c(0,1))

year_gg <- c(rep("0-9Years" , 2) , rep("10-19Years" , 2) , rep("20-29Years" , 2) , rep("30-39Years" , 2),rep("40- 49Years", 2),rep("50-59Years", 2),rep("60-69Years" , 2),rep("70-79Years", 2),rep("80+Years", 2))
subgroup = rep(c("Death_Hosp","Death_Non_Hosp"),9)
value = as.vector(t(cbind(hosp_death_rate, non_hosp_death_rate)))
data_gg <- data.frame(year_gg,subgroup,value)

# Grouped
ggplot(data_gg, aes(fill=subgroup, y=value, x=year_gg)) + 
  geom_bar(position="dodge", stat="identity")

people has a lower death rate for not staying in hospital? Why

for people show symptoms, calculate hospitalized rate vs month change

df_month_hosp = na.omit(data.frame(df_symptom$symptom_month, df_symptom$hosp_yn,df_symptom$death_yn))
df_month_hosp[df_month_hosp=="Missing"|df_month_hosp=="Unknown"]<- NA
df_month_hosp = na.omit(df_month_hosp)

symptom_hosp = rep(0,10)
for (m in 1:10){
  df_temp = df_month_hosp[df_month_hosp$df_symptom.symptom_month==m,]
  symptom_hosp[m] = sum(df_temp$df_symptom.hosp_yn=="Yes")/dim(df_temp)[1]
}
barplot(symptom_hosp,names.arg=1:10, ylab = "hospitalized rate for patients showing sypotoms", xlab="month in 2020")

# hospitalized death over month
symptom_death_hosp = rep(0,10)
for (m in 1:10){
  df_temp = df_month_hosp[df_month_hosp$df_symptom.symptom_month==m,]
  symptom_death_hosp[m] = sum(df_temp$df_symptom.hosp_yn=="Yes" & df_temp$df_symptom.death_yn=="Yes")/dim(df_temp)[1]
}
barplot(symptom_death_hosp,names.arg=1:10, ylab = "hospitalized rate for patients showing sypotoms", xlab="month in 2020")

# non-hospitalized death over month
symptom_death_non_hosp = rep(0,10)
for (m in 1:10){
  df_temp = df_month_hosp[df_month_hosp$df_symptom.symptom_month==m,]
  symptom_death_non_hosp[m] = sum(df_temp$df_symptom.hosp_yn=="No" & df_temp$df_symptom.death_yn=="Yes")/dim(df_temp)[1]
}
barplot(symptom_death_non_hosp,names.arg=1:10, ylab = "hospitalized rate for patients showing sypotoms", xlab="month in 2020")

month_gg <- c(rep("1" , 2) , rep("2" , 2) , rep("3" , 2) , rep("4" , 2),rep("5", 2),rep("6", 2),rep("7" , 2),rep("8", 2),rep("9", 2),rep("10", 2))
subgroup = rep(c("Death_Hosp","Death_Non_Hosp"),10)
value = as.vector(t(cbind(symptom_death_hosp, symptom_death_non_hosp)))
data_gg <- data.frame(month_gg,subgroup,value)

# Grouped
ggplot(data_gg, aes(fill=subgroup, y=value, x=month_gg)) + 
  geom_bar(position="dodge", stat="identity")

It’s obviously death rate for hospitalized patients are much higher in Feb, March, and April, compared to other month, this is probably due to cross-infections in the hospital at that time, and not enough medical resources.

Another possibilities could be patients admitted into hospitals are old and have underlying diseases.

1) Old people is more likely to die from COVID19

It shows people with medical conditions have much higher chance of passing away in the pademic, especially for those mid-aged to senior aged.

And old people have higher ratio in having medical conditions among to their peers.

medcond_rate = rep(0,length(age_range))

Does pre-screening help reducing the death rate. (Pre-screening is defined as test positive before showing symptoms)

# Positive before symptom VS after symptom ~ survival rate
df_complete_time <- df_confirmed[-union(which(is.na(df_confirmed$pos_spec_dt)),which(is.na(df_confirmed$onset_dt))),]

date_diff = as.Date(as.character(df_complete_time$onset_dt),format="%Y/%m/%d") - as.Date(as.character(df_complete_time$pos_spec_dt),format="%Y/%m/%d")
df_complete_time$date_diff = date_diff

df_complete_time = na.omit(data.frame(df_complete_time$death_yn, df_complete_time$age_group, df_complete_time$medcond_yn,df_complete_time$date_diff))
df_complete_time[df_complete_time=="Missing"|df_complete_time=="Unknown"]<- NA
df_complete_time = na.omit(df_complete_time)

pre_screening = df_complete_time[df_complete_time$df_complete_time.date_diff<0,]
symptom_show = df_complete_time[df_complete_time$df_complete_time.date_diff>=0,]

# screening vs death rate
sum(pre_screening$df_complete_time.death_yn=="Yes")/dim(pre_screening)[1]
## [1] 0.03232202
sum(symptom_show$df_complete_time.death_yn=="Yes")/dim(symptom_show)[1]
## [1] 0.07047638

It shows pre-screening can lower the death rate from 7% to 3%.

Let’s see which age group does the most screening

# pre-screening rate ~ age
pre_screening_age = rep(0,length(age_range))
# head(pre_screening)
for (y in 1:length(age_range)){
  pre_screening_age[y] = dim(pre_screening[as.character(pre_screening$df_complete_time.age_group)==age_range[y],])[1]
}
barplot(pre_screening_age,names.arg=age_range, ylab = "Number of people do prescreening", xlab="age range")

The mid-aged groups do the most of screening.

for th people do pre-screening, death rate in age?

prescreening_death_rate = rep(0,length(age_range))
for (y in 1:length(age_range)){
  df_temp = pre_screening[as.character(pre_screening$df_complete_time.age_group)==age_range[y],]
  prescreening_death_rate[y] = sum(df_temp$df_complete_time.medcond_yn=="Yes")/dim(df_temp)[1]
}
barplot(prescreening_death_rate,names.arg=age_range, ylab = "Pre-screening death rate", xlab="age range", ylim=c(0,1))

# people dont do pre-screening (symptom show), death rate in age?
symptom_show_death_rate = rep(0,length(age_range))
for (y in 1:length(age_range)){
  df_temp = symptom_show[as.character(symptom_show$df_complete_time.age_group)==age_range[y],]
  symptom_show_death_rate[y] = sum(df_temp$df_complete_time.medcond_yn=="Yes")/dim(df_temp)[1]
}
barplot(symptom_show_death_rate,names.arg=age_range, ylab = "Non screening death rate", xlab="age range", ylim=c(0,1))

# ggplot
month_gg <- c(rep("0-9Years" , 2) , rep("10-19Years" , 2) , rep("20-29Years" , 2) , rep("30-39Years" , 2),rep("40- 49Years", 2),rep("50-59Years", 2),rep("60-69Years" , 2),rep("70-79Years", 2),rep("80+Years", 2))

# Grouped
ggplot(data_gg, aes(fill=subgroup, y=value, x=month_gg)) + 
  geom_bar(position="dodge", stat="identity")

For younger groups, the screening doesnt lower death rate, but for old groups, it helps reducing the death rate.
